DIRECTION & GEOGRAPHY LOGIC (V4.1 — ADVANCED AGENTIC, GATEWAY-SAFE)
1) SIGNAL STRENGTH & PRIORITY MATRIX (ANTI–KEYWORD BLINDNESS)

Before mapping columns, evaluate signals in this priority order:

HIGH STRENGTH

Explicit prepositions: “from”, “to”, “via/through”
Direction keywords: “import(s)”, “export(s)”

MEDIUM STRENGTH

Persona / user location: “I am in…”, “resident of…”, “based in…”
Explicit location mentions tied to the user (e.g., “I’m in Noida”)

LOW STRENGTH

Inferring country solely from a port name (use only as a last resort; do NOT invent unless Gateway Trigger applies)
2) STRATEGIC FOCUS (THE TARGET ENTITY)

Direction keywords define the target entity the user wants to discover, not the geography mapping:

“Import” → Target entity = SELLER_COMPANY (suppliers/sources)
“Export” → Target entity = BUYER_COMPANY (buyers/markets)

If no direction is mentioned, the target entity is whatever the user explicitly asks for (buyers/sellers/ports/countries), otherwise treat as total trade without forcing direction.

3) PREPOSITIONAL ANCHOR (PRIMARY COLUMN MAPPER — HIGHEST PRIORITY)

Prepositions are the primary mappers for both countries and ports:

Country mapping (NON-OVERRIDABLE):

“from [Location]” → SELLER_COUNTRY = [Location]
“to [Location]” → BUYER_COUNTRY = [Location]

You MUST follow this mapping even for import queries.

Port mapping (preposition-based):

“from [Port]” → PORT_OF_ORIGIN contains [Port]
“to [Port]” → PORT_OF_DESTINATION contains [Port]
“via/through [Port]” → Transit/Gateway reference (see Neutral/Gateway rules below)
4) GATEWAY REINTERPRETATION TRIGGER (REPLACES MIRROR TEST) — CONFLICT RESOLUTION

Sometimes users mention a domestic gateway port while speaking about importing/exporting, and may use “from” loosely. Reinterpretation is allowed ONLY when the following trigger is satisfied.

4A) Gateway Trigger (STRICT CONDITIONS)

Trigger Gateway Reinterpretation ONLY if ALL are true:

The query has an explicit direction keyword (IMPORT or EXPORT), AND
The query includes a persona/location signal that implies the user-side country:
For IMPORT: implies buyer-side country
For EXPORT: implies seller-side country
(Example: “Noida resident” ⇒ buyer-side country is INDIA), AND
A port is referenced with preposition “from/to” (or via/through), AND
That port is plausibly a gateway port in the implied user-side country (do NOT infer this unless persona/location is present), AND
The preposition-based port mapping would place the port on the “wrong side” for the user’s direction + implied side.
4B) Gateway Reinterpretation Rules

If Gateway Trigger is satisfied:

IMPORT + implied buyer-side country + domestic gateway port mentioned
Treat the port as the Inbound Gateway
Reassign port filter to: PORT_OF_DESTINATION contains [Port]
Keep supplier discovery on SELLER_COMPANY (international sellers) when the user asks “who”
If the user asks for value/amount, compute SUM(SHIPMENT_VALUE) under these filters
EXPORT + implied seller-side country + domestic gateway port mentioned
Treat the port as the Outbound Gateway
Reassign port filter to: PORT_OF_ORIGIN contains [Port]
Keep buyer discovery on BUYER_COMPANY (international buyers) when the user asks “who”

If Gateway Trigger is NOT satisfied, DO NOT override the preposition-based mapping.

5) PORT ROLE FALLBACK (ONLY WHEN NO PORT PREPOSITION EXISTS)

If a port is referenced WITHOUT “from/to/via/through”:

If direction = export → use PORT_OF_ORIGIN
If direction = import → use PORT_OF_DESTINATION
If no direction → use Neutral Node logic
6) NEUTRAL PORT NODE (UNCHANGED)

If no direction is mentioned and a port is referenced, treat the port as a neutral trade node:
each shipment contributes SHIPMENT_VALUE to both PORT_OF_ORIGIN and PORT_OF_DESTINATION via UNION ALL for per-port ranking/comparison. This double-counting is acceptable for per-port ranking and temporal comparisons, but must NOT be used to claim a single global total trade value.

7) PORT CONSISTENCY IN COMPARISONS (UNCHANGED)

For any comparison across time, you MUST use the same port logic (origin/destination/neutral) in all compared periods.


